# Documentation (The top header should be in title case)

## Where detail belongs

| Audience | Location | Content |
|----------|----------|---------|
| Template/user consumers | README or `docs/` | Usage, conventions, examples |
| Developers changing code | Source files | JSDoc, docstrings, variable descriptions, non-obvious logic |
| System overview | `docs/` or top-level README | Concepts, architecture, how to extend |

**README rules:** scope, no file inventories, general not implementation-specific —
see [readme.mdc](readme.mdc).

File-specific behavior always lives in the implementing source file, not in a
README that lists that file.

## In-source documentation

File- and module-level docs should read professionally and follow the language's
conventions:

| Language | Convention |
|----------|------------|
| TypeScript / JavaScript | JSDoc on modules and exports; `@param`, `@returns`, `@example` when helpful |
| Python | Module docstring; Google or NumPy style for functions and classes |
| Go | Package comment above `package`; doc comment on exported names |
| Rust | `//!` for module/crate docs; `///` on public items |
| Java | Javadoc (`/** … */`) on types and public members |
| Kotlin | KDoc on public API; `@param`, `@return`, `@sample` when helpful |
| C# | XML doc comments (`///`) on public types and members |
| Ruby | YARD/RDoc above methods and classes; `@param`, `@return`, `@example` |
| Swift | `///` line docs or `/** … */` blocks on public API |
| PHP | PHPDoc on classes, methods, and properties |
| Shell (sh/bash) | File header comment (purpose, usage); function comment before each function |
| Terraform / HCL | `description` on every `variable` and `output`; `#` comments for non-obvious resource logic |

### Terraform / HCL

- Put **input and output documentation** in `description` on the `variable` and
  `output` blocks — not duplicated per-field in README.
- Module README: consumer usage, examples, and high-level behavior (see
  [readme.mdc](readme.mdc)); link to or summarize inputs/outputs without
  replacing `description` text.
- Use `#` comments sparingly for non-obvious wiring, lifecycle choices, or
  provider quirks — not to restate what the HCL already shows.
- Align with [terraform-module-standard.mdc](terraform-module-standard.mdc) for
  module repo structure.

### General guidelines

- Lead with **purpose** — what this module or export does and when to use it.
- Document public API (inputs, outputs, side effects); skip obvious internals.
- Use `@example` or language equivalent for non-trivial usage.
- Inline comments: non-obvious business rules only, not restating the code.

Prefer in-source API docs over a README section that repeats the same detail.

## docs/ directory

Create a `docs/` directory only when the repo has **distinct subjects** that
deserve standalone guides — topics too broad for a co-located README or a single
package README, and not better served by in-source docs alone.

**Add a doc when:**

- A cross-cutting system or workflow spans multiple packages (e.g. scaffolder
  actions + fields + backend API).
- Operators or integrators need a guide that outgrows the root README.
- A subject is **unique to this repo** — not generic framework usage already
  covered upstream.

**Do not create `docs/` for:**

- Content that fits a co-located README's scope.
- File inventories or per-module API reference (belongs in source).
- Thin wrappers with nothing repo-specific to explain.

Root README should link to `docs/` when it exists; keep the root README as entry
point, not a duplicate of every guide.

### Architecture

When the repo has a non-trivial structure (multiple services, plugins, deployment
stages, or data flows), add `docs/architecture.md` (or equivalent) that explains
how the pieces fit together.

- Prefer a **diagram** — mermaid for flows and components, or ASCII when simpler.
- Cover boundaries, major integrations, and extension points — not a file tree.
- Update the diagram when architecture changes materially.

```markdown
<!-- GOOD: docs/architecture.md excerpt -->
## Scaffolder flow

Template repo `content/` → gel-template-content API → field extensions → actions → fetch:template
```

## docs/ writing guidelines

- Explain **what** and **why**, not a map of the repo.
- Describe extension by **concept**, not by listing every file to touch.
- Only create or expand docs when asked, or when a new cross-cutting subject
  needs a consumer- or operator-facing guide.

## Markdown style

- Max ~100 characters per line unless a table or code block needs more.
- Complete sentences; link to external sources when citing specs or APIs.
